obverseDescription: Forward facing crowned bust within a triangle, a cinquefoil with hollow centre to the right of the bust. Features of this obverse design are difficult to determine, with the exception of the cinquefoil, and it appears to be set within a lozenge rather than a triangle. This suggests that the coin might have been double struck on the obverse as well as the reverse flan. Doublestruck.
reverseDescription: Voided long cross with three pellets per quarter. No single pellet is visible at the centre of the voided cross but if one was present this might have been obscured from view by the double strike and/or the coin being cut in half over this centre point. This reverse has been double struck with an extra arm of another cross passing from the centre of the flan to the edge of the coin through the letter 'N' following the O. It is the presence of this arm that obscures the letter 'N' from view making it illegible.
obverseLegend: [h]ENRI/CV[R/EX III] with the N and R probably ligated

The hair is formed with two curls either side with central pellets, the eyes are annulets with central pellets. The chin and beard is formed from a two large central pellets with two rows each of three pellets either side. The neck / shoulders are not shown. In the inscription teh E is round backed and closed, the Nand R are ligatured and the R has a wedge shaped tail, C round backed and closed, X plain,
